name: Babergh
description_1: Babergh District includes some of the most traditionally attractive villages that Suffolk is famous for– the former wool towns of Lavenham, Long Melford and Hadleigh, as well as Sudbury (also well-known for its silk-weaving heritage). The District is bordered to the east by the Orwell Estuary and to the south by the Stour estuary, and the north-eastern boundary links with the southern (and most deprived) wards of Ipswich. However the majority of Babergh’s residents live in rural communities – Hadleigh and Sudbury are the only sizable towns.
description_2: Communities: Babergh’s overall indices of deprivation score is lower than for Suffolk as a whole but higher for barriers to housing and services, such as transport and access to GPs surgeries. These scores disguise some significant inequalities – Great Cornard, a large London over-spill development of the 1970s at Sudbury, ranks among the highest IDM scores in Suffolk, alongside Sudbury East and South, whereas parts of Hadleigh and Holbrook are among the least deprived. Even the beautiful tourist destination of Long Melford hides pockets of significant deprivation. In fact, Babergh District has one of the highest proportion of children living in income deprived households in Suffolk.
description_3: Education:  attainment at KS4 is better than the Suffolk average and there is a lower than average number of NEETs. This is data from 2017 and possibly gives the lie to the Social Mobility Index’s poor ranking for Babergh based on figures that are now 4 years old. In the report it is ranked 49th out of the 65 LAs deemed to be the 20% of social mobility cold spots, and it scores particularly badly (12th out of 32) in terms of schools performance, improving at post 16.
description_4: Cultural Offer:: Babergh has a wealth of interesting heritage sites and churches and some excellent local museums, including Gainsborough House in Sudbury, Wattisham Station Heritage (part of an active MoD site) and the various National Trust properties associated with John Constable around Flatford Mill and East Bergholt. The Quay Theatre in Sudbury offers a regular programme of plays and cinema, including live streaming or reruns of live theatre from the National Theatre and elsewhere.

name: Breckland
description_1: Breckland is located to the west of Norwich, running from just south of Fakenham (in North Norfolk) to Thetford. It is a largely rural District, though a third of the population do live in urban areas (towns with a population of more than 10,000) including Thetford, Dereham and Swaffham.
description_2: An emerging Local Cultural Education Partnership, the Heart of East Anglia, is developing to serve Thetford.
description_3: Communities: Breckland has a much higher level of children and young people in workless households, which has increased significantly in the past 3 years, and some of its wards, especially in Thetford, are among the most deprived in England – Thetford Abbey ward is among the 10% most deprived in England. There is also clear evidence, as elsewhere in Norfolk, prosperity alongside poverty in the same towns. Thetford particularly shows wide inequality in child poverty, which ranges from 5.7% in Thetford Guildhall ward to 41.9% in Thetford Saxon.
description_4: The number of children living in workless households in Breckland is much worse than Norfolk and England averages – it is the highest number in Norfolk and has risen rapidly from 5.6% in 2011 to 21% in 2013. Breckland unfortunately also has a higher than average incidence of domestic violence than elsewhere in Norfolk. However homelessness is lower than in other Districts.
description_5: Education: Achievement is average for England and improving. The achievement gap between disadvantaged children and others is lowest in the early years which indicates likely improvement over time. Children’s achievements at Key Stage 2 have improved in the last two years, but the overall achievement rate (68% Level 4 Maths and Literacy) is well below the national average and lowest in the county. At KS4, young people’s achievements is in line with the Norfolk average (55%) but lower than national average. However it is clear from comparing the data that children from income deprived households do significantly worse than others.
description_6: Social mobility: In Breckland is poor. It ranks 19th in the Social Mobility Index’s coldspots listing – the worst ranking 20% of 65 local authorities. Many areas of social deprivation still score well for social mobility but unfortunately Breckland, like the majority of Norfolk’s second tier local authorities, scores badly.
description_7: Cultural Offer: Breckland has a number of interesting museums and heritage assets, including Gressenhall Farm and Workhouse, Ancient House Museum and Charles Burrell Museum in Thetford, and Swaffham Museum (which focuses on social history of Swaffham and its surrounding villages) fewer children and young people are involved in positive activities outside school in Breckland, and there are fewer active library borrowers (though more than both Great Yarmouth and King’s Lynn).

name: Broadland
description_1: Broadland District is one of the most prosperous local authorities in Norfolk, second only to South Norfolk. It encompasses the eastern part of greater Norwich and half of its residents live in urban areas. Broadland also encompasses a section of the Norfolk and Suffolk Broads National Park. This part of Norfolk is a popular tourist destination: the Broads as a whole attracted more than 7 million visitors in 2015 with an economic impact of £584 million. As this section of the Broads is the largest it is safe to say the Broadland benefits significantly from this especially as a source of employment – 7245 jobs are dependent on Broads tourism overall.
description_2: Communities: Broadland has the lowest rate of child poverty in the county, and below English averages, but the numbers have grown in the past two years. Like other Norfolk Districts, Broadland has a Youth Advisory Board with its own budget to commission participatory activities for children and young people particularly in areas of need such as Aylsham and Acle. These two towns particularly have significant pockets of deprivation with 18.6% of families living on low incomes.
description_3: Social Mobility: Broadland does not score very highly in terms of social mobility of which it is average – neither in the top 20% of social mobility hot spots, nor in the lowest 20% coldspots. However with half its population located in the urban greater Norwich area, this data needs interrogating at ward level.
description_4: Education: It also has the lowest number of young people not in education, employment or training. It is above average for educational attainment and this is improving, with girls performing better than boys.
description_5: Cultural Offer: Broadland District has few cultural assets of its own beyond the built heritage of medieval churches, remnants of the Broads industrial past such as wind pumps and some historic villages, but its proximity to Norwich means that residents can benefit from those based in the city.

name: Cambridge
description_1: My Cambridge is the Local Cultural Education Partnership serving the city.
description_2: Cambridge is the economic and political centre of Cambridgeshire, and thanks to its world class and ancient university it is also a magnate for research-led business and tourism. It has high job density, with employment in higher education and research and development 10 and 8 times the national average respectively. There is also a large tourism sector. However this success also has its downsides – there is a high level of in-commuting leading to constant traffic congestion, and the increasing number of tourists, especially day tourists, can lead to local tensions and over-crowded streets.
description_3: Cambridge is a highly entrepreneurial town, but there is employment disparity with the more deprived parts of the city where the population is less skilled and do not benefit from the growth.
description_4: Demographic: Cambridge has the highest net migration of all Cambridgeshire second tier local authorities – more than two-thirds higher than Fenland. The majority of these are highly skilled workers or members of the universities; however there is also a significant minority of less-skilled migrants from EU A8 countries (eastern European) clustered in parts of Cambridge. Primary schools in the Cambridge City district area with the highest proportion of pupils who speak an A8 language are located in the Arbury, Kings Hedges and Chesterton areas – on the north side of Cambridge city. These areas are also among the most deprived in Cambridgeshire, with LSOAs in the top 20% of deprivation, indicating significant inequalities in the city.
description_5: Education: While educational attainment is generally high, this is boosted by non-Cambridge residents – attainment among children and young people resident in Cambridge is lower. In addition there is a relatively high proportion of young people aged 16-19 who are not in education, employment or training in spite of the buoyant jobs market in the city.  Cambridge is categorised as 3 out of 6 in the 2016 Education White Paper.
description_6: Social Mobility: This is reflected in the Social Mobility Index, where Cambridge scores very badly considering the benefits it offers. It stands 275 out of the 324 65 local authorities and is thus categorised as a Social Mobility cold spot. This indicates that in relation to those from disadvantaged backgrounds who do relatively badly at school it is symptomatic of significant inequalities between rich and poor. It is also one of the lowest performing 10% of local areas conditional upon area deprivation (excluding London) standing at 16th out of 29, and when it comes of indicators around youth social mobility it is the 5th worst out of the bottom 32 authorities.
description_7: Cultural Offer: Cambridge has of course a wealth of cultural assets – not least the university buildings themselves. Cambridge is home to several Arts Council NPOs, including UCM (University of Cambridge Museums), Britten Sinfonia, Hoipolloi Theatre Company, the Academy of Ancient Music and Kettle’s Yard. The Arts Theatre has a year round programme of touring theatre and The Junction combines a well-established music venue with a wide range of performing arts programming. A new arts venue is opening in the north of the city in 2017 as part of extensive housing development there.

name: East Cambridgeshire
description_1: The main town is Ely, which is the administrative centre for the District, and is physically dominated by the imposing bulk of Ely Cathedral (the so-called Ship of the Fens). East Cambridgeshire is essentially a fenland area though the countryside around Newmarket becomes more like neighbouring Suffolk.
description_2: East Cambridgeshire is very well connected. Ely is a major railway hub connecting fast trains to Cambridge and London, and to Ipswich, Norwich, Peterborough and the north, Birmingham and Stansted Airport. With the A10 running through it, there is also a regular bus service to Cambridge.
description_3: Economy: Like Fenland, the economy of East Cambridgeshire is dominated by agriculture. However, it is also becoming a dormitory for Cambridge, and unemployment is below average. The population is growing, with extensive developments in Ely, Littleport and Soham during the past two decades, which have also driven house prices up by more than 50% since 2001.
description_4: Communities: Although East Cambridgeshire is considerably less deprived than Fenland and even Cambridge, it has areas of high deprivation, especially in and around Littleport, Ely and Soham (its three largest areas of urbanisation). Rankings in these areas have declined significantly since 2010.
description_5: Education: Education and skills in the District are generally improving. Yet the DFE Education Excellence Everywhere 2016 placed the district in the bottom sextile.
description_6: Social Mobility: The Social Mobility Index shows that although, overall East Cambridgeshire does not score particularly badly for deprivation the district ranks as high as 311th worst area for social mobility out of 324 districts in the country.
description_7: The Department for Education has designated Fenland and East Cambridgeshire a joint Opportunity Area to improve social mobility.
description_8: Cultural Offer: Though close to Cambridge, East Cambridgeshire has many cultural assets in its own right, including Ely Cathedral and the Stained Glass Museum located inside it, Babylon Arts and Gallery in Ely, Burwell Museum, Stretham Old Engine and Anglesey Abbey. The Ouse Washes (built in the 17th century to drain the fens) are still an important wildlife habitat, and the National Stud is located between Soham and Newmarket.

name: Fenland
description_1: The Young Fenland cultural Consortium is the Local Cultural Education Partnership in the region.
description_2: The District as a whole is largely rural and agriculture is its main economic driver, due to the rich fenland peat. Its main towns are Wisbech, March, Whittlesey and Chatteris, where 75% of its population lives.
description_3: Communities: Fenland is the most deprived District in Cambridgeshire, with 12 of the most deprived LSOAs located in the District, of which 4 in Wisbech are among the 10% most deprived areas in England. This level of deprivation has actually increased between 2010 and 2015 during which time Fenland went from 94th to 80th most deprived local authority in the country.
description_4: Industry: The economy is built on farming and food related industry.
description_5: Population: The fresh food industry has drawn in a fairly large proportion of economic migrants from central and eastern Europe in the past 5-10 years, of which the majority are adults of working age, with the majority aged between 25 and 34. There is a concentration of Polish, Latvian and especially Lithuanian workers in Wisbech and though few have more than one dependent child this is putting some strain on primary schools mainly because parents’ English skills are poor and need translators in meetings, or cannot attend meetings because they work unsocial hours. It is worth noting however, that Fenland does not have the highest level of net migration in Cambridgeshire – it has only a third of the level of Cambridge.
description_6: Education: Fenland was ranked in the lowest sextile, in the Local Authority District indicators used to model Achieving Excellence Areas in 2016’s White Paper Education Excellence Everywhere
description_7: Social Mobility: Fenland has scored poorly in the Social Mobility Index, ranked sixth in the Index’s worst performing cold spots nationally. It is the worst performing local authority overall in terms of school social mobility indicators, and as such has been designated an Opportunity Area, alongside its neighbouring local authority East Cambridgeshire, by the Department for Education, in order to address some of the issues that the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission have highlighted in their report.
description_8: Cultural Offer: Fenland has many interesting cultural assets, including its unique landscape itself. There are four important SSSIs in the District, including the RSPB Ouse Fen, and interesting heritage sites include Peckover House (National Trust) in Wisbech, Wisbech and Fenland Museum, Whittlesey Museum, and the Angles Theatre in Wisbech. Arts Council England noted however that fewer than 20% of the population regularly engage with arts and culture and as such have funded a Creative People and Places initiative there to encourage participation.

name: Forest Heath
description_1: Forest Heath District Council is the most westerly District in Suffolk, bordered mainly by Cambridgeshire, but also to the north, with Norfolk.
description_2: An emerging Local Cultural Education Partnership, the Heart of East Anglia, is developing to serve this area.
description_3: Communities: The boundaries of Forest Heath include one of the biggest concentrations of United States Visiting Forces in the UK, in the large US Air Force bases at Mildenhall and Lakenheath. It is the highest concentration of any non-British population in the east of England and makes up 18% of the population. This skews the data considerably: for instance, currently children at school in the military bases get counted in to the data, and this tends to make Forest Heath’s indices of deprivation appear better than they are. Suffolk County Council and Forest Heath DC are looking to work with US officials to find better ways of measuring the data.
description_4: Forest Heath has in recent years combined much of its administration with the neighbouring District of St Edmundsbury as a joint West Suffolk authority but the geography of the two Districts is very distinct.
description_5: Cultural Offer: Forest Heath has few cultural assets within its boundaries, but the recently (2016) enlarged and refurbished National Heritage Centre for Horse Racing and Sporting Art at Newmarket is an important new development, and was a finalist for the Art Fund’s Museum of the Year 2017. The proximity to Cambridge and Ely means that residents of Forest Heath do have access to high quality arts and culture though the Taking Part survey shows that currently fewer than 20% of residents have regular engagement of culture and there is a Creative People and Places initiative based in the District to address this.

name: Great Yarmouth
description_1: The Borough of Great Yarmouth is largely based in the urban area of the coastal resort of great Yarmouth (71% of its population live there), but also encompasses some of the agricultural and marsh of the immediate hinterland. Great Yarmouth used to be centre for herring fishing plus a popular sea side resort with a long safe sandy beach, but these declined as elsewhere in the UK with the depletion of herring stocks and the increase in tourism travel outside the UK. This is reflected in the economic decline of the town and the rise in poverty, although the off-shore energy industry is fuelling a slow up-turn. Great Yarmouth is also the mouth of one of the major rivers of the Norfolk Broads, the Yare, which runs from Norwich to the sea.
description_2: The Local Cultural Education Partnership’ Enjoy: Great Yarmouth’ serves this area.
description_3: Communities: 22.68% of Great Yarmouth’s population are aged 0-19 which is higher than any other local authority area in Norfolk, but lower than the national average. Great Yarmouth has higher rates of child poverty and income deprivation than other parts of Norfolk, though there is a lower level of workless households. There are significant differences in equality between wards, ranging from 5% in part of Gorleston to 67% in Nelson ward, which is the highest rate anywhere in Norfolk. Nine of the LSOAs in Great Yarmouth are in the 10% most deprived in England.
description_4: Education: Attainment is lower than the Norfolk average, though it is improving, but there is a higher than average number of young people who are NEET.
description_5: Social Mobility: Great Yarmouth is also a social mobility cold-spot, as are many declining coastal towns, numbering among the worst performing 20% local authorities in England. It ranks at 28 out of 65, though slightly better than its immediate neighbour Lowestoft (Waveney D.C.).
description_6: Cultural Offer: Great Yarmouth has an interesting heritage and there are several high-profile cultural assets and organisations in the Borough. Seachange Arts is an Arts Council NPO and is a national centre for circus and outdoor arts, as well as running the annual Out There festival in the town. The iconic Hippodrome is one of the last purpose built circus venues in England, hosting a wide variety of performances and shows, while St George’s Theatre is also a central venue for performances. Great Yarmouth also has a number of museums, including Time and Tide (based at the old herring smoking premises), the Nelson Museum and the Elizabeth House Museums. Many of these organisations provide programmes and activities for children and young people.

name: Huntingdonshire
description_1: The Top Secret at Alconbury Weald Local Cultural Education Partnership is active in this area.
description_2: Huntingdonshire lies on Cambridgeshire’s north-west border. The District used to be a small county in its own right but was incorporated into Cambridgeshire in the late 20th century. As such, the District has a distinct character, both geographically and psychologically.
description_3: Demographics: The population of the District in 2015 was 175,700 and it is growing, with major developments in places such as Alconbury – site of a former USAF base. It is the largest District in Cambridgeshire in terms of population. Huntingdonshire has one of the highest number of residents of Asian and African/African Caribbean heritage in the county (outside Cambridge), with the largest concentration in Huntingdon North, which was developed as a London overspill area in the 1970s.
description_4: Communities: Huntingdonshire is a fairly prosperous district, second only to South Cambridgeshire in the county, though deprivation has slightly increased overall since 2010. The most deprived indicators are education and barriers to housing. Deprivation is highest in Huntingdon North and St Neots Eynesbury wards, but even so their level of deprivation marginally improved between 2010 and 2015 and they are no longer in Cambridgeshire’s 10% most deprived LSOAs.
description_5: Education: the district was ranked in the lowest sextile, in the Local Authority District indicators used to model Achieving Excellence Areas in 2016’s White Paper Education Excellence Everywhere
description_6: Employment: The local economy is agricultural and knowledge-based, and its good transport links mean that many people commute out of the District for work. Self-employment levels are above regional and national levels, and business resilience is better than national, regional and all other Cambridgeshire districts. Social mobility in Huntingdonshire is not classified as a cold Spot however the school aged categories of the Social Mobility Index flagged the area as the 300 worst out of 324 district areas.
description_7: Cultural Offer: As elsewhere in Cambridgeshire, Huntingdonshire has an interesting heritage. It is particularly associated with Oliver Cromwell who was born and brought up in Huntingdon, and the Cromwell Museum is dedicated to his life and career. There are many interesting buildings in Huntingdon, including the George Hotel which hosts site specific Shakespeare productions every summer. Other important cultural assets include Hinchinbrooke House, Houghton Mill and the Norris Museum in St Ives, and the St Neots Museum.

name: Ipswich
description_1: Ipswich is the largest town in Suffolk and is the administrative centre for both Suffolk County Council and the Borough Council. It lies on edge of the River Orwell estuary, and has a thriving yacht marina and a small working seaport. Its proximity to Felixstowe, accessible by trunk road across the Orwell Bridge, also provides significant employment and the town is also home to the new University of Suffolk which is based in the redeveloped riverside area. The town is also well connected: it is a railway hub, with regular trains to London and Norwich, and connections to Lowestoft, Felixstowe, Bury St Edmunds and Cambridge, and links by road to the A14 and the A12.
description_2: An emerging Local Cultural Education Partnership is developing to serve this area.
description_3: Communities: Ipswich has suffered from a fall in local employment opportunities over the past 30-40 years and there are significant areas of deprivation: more than half of its 16 wards are in the top 10% of most deprived wards in England, and there are over 80 LSOAs. There is a distinct geographical division in terms of deprivation in the town – with the western and southern wards seeing the most deprivation.
description_4: Education: Average educational achievement, though improving, is poor overall (though this is subject to wide differences depending on the deprivation levels of the wards), with only 46.4% of pupils overall achieving 5+ A*-C in GCSE (including maths and English). But at LSOA level, there are lower scores than this – several under 30% and one at only 9%.
description_5: Social Mobility: Ipswich is among the 20% of local authority cold spots in the UK in terms of social mobility. It scores particularly poorly in terms of its performance against school social mobility indicators (8th worst in England and Wales) and therefore, like Norwich, is benefitting from additional funding for the next 3 years (from 2017) from the DfE’s Opportunity Areas initiative.
description_6: Cultural Offer: The town has an historic centre and extensive parks, and has the largest concentration of Arts Council National Portfolio Organisations (NPOs) in the east of England – seven in all - including the New Wolsey Theatre, DanceEast (the regional centre for dance), and well-established touring theatre company Eastern Angles. Ipswich also is home to one of two Championship professional football clubs in the east, and like many clubs undertakes significant community development work. There is considerable cultural collaboration between Ipswich and Colchester (its nearest neighbour of equivalent size, in north-east Essex), and Ipswich and Colchester Museums have recently been awarded joint NPO status by Arts Council England, a recognition of the high standard of their work.

name: King's Lynn & West Norfolk
description_1: The Borough of King’s Lynn and West Norfolk (KLWN) covers the largest geographic area of any District or Borough in Norfolk.  The Borough’s western boundary is with the north Cambridgeshire fens, and people living there have more in common with their Fenland neighbours than those living in the more traditional agricultural landscape of Norfolk. The borough also has a coastal strip, alongside the Wash, with Hunstanton as the biggest town – a coastal resort that like many others has declined in recent decades.
description_2: King’s Lynn: is strategically placed on a fast rail ink to Ely, Cambrige and London and as such is experiencing increased housing development. It has become an Historic England Heritage Action Zone. King’s Lynn has been an important North Sea port since medieval times and has many important heritage buildings, and the Heritage Action Zone will help the Borough ensure its new developments are in keeping with its heritage. It also comes with support for schools in using heritage in their learning.
description_3: Communities: KLWN has lower rates of deprivation overall but there are high levels of inequality within that, ranging from 1.7% in Airfield ward to 42.5% in South & West Lynn. Unemployment is also higher than the average for Norfolk. While a third of its population live in its main urban areas of King’s Lynn, Hunstanton and Downham Market the Borough is largely rural. Unusually for Norfolk, the main second language in the area is Lithuanian, rather than Polish or Portuguese.
description_4: Education: The borough also has below average educational attainment, and many small rural primary schools are struggling to maintain standards.
description_5: Social Mobility: though KLWN is among the Social Mobility Index’s 20% of cold spots in England, it is by no means the worst in Norfolk, at 32 out of 65.
description_6: Cultural Offer: King’s Lynn and the surrounding villages have many cultural assets, particularly in terms of heritage buildings (even the main library in King’s Lynn is itself a listed building), and there is an active learning network among the heritage providers and museums. The Borough includes Castle Rising, Castle Acre and priory, Houghton Hall, and also Sandringham House, one of the Queen’s main country residences. The Corn Exchange in King’s Lynn is the main venue for the long-standing King’s Lynn Festival – formerly mainly classical music but now widening its programme and beginning to take activity to surrounding villages. Since the closure of the Arts Centre in 2015 KLWN council and others are consulting on a new cultural strategy for the space.

name: Mid Suffolk
description_1: Mid-Suffolk District Council runs from close to Diss and the Norfolk county border down to the suburbs of Ipswich in the south. The council has combined administrations with Babergh, which not only borders it to the south, but is also one of its 16 statistical neighbours in terms of demographics and economic activity. It is a highly rural area with Stowmarket its only sizable town. The District is bisected north to south by the main A140 Norwich to Ipswich road, and east to west by the A14 trunk road. It also has the advantage of being on the mainline from Norwich, Ipswich and London though this only stops at Stowmarket. However other transport links are patchy at best.
description_2: An emerging Local Cultural Education Partnership, the Heart of East Anglia, is developing to serve this area.
description_3: Communities: Mid-Suffolk is the least deprived District in Suffolk. These statistics however hide some less favourable data. The District has seen a significant increase in deprivation in some areas since 2007 (latest figures are from 2015). These show wide inequalities – although Mid-Suffolk has the fewest children in Suffolk living in households affected by income deprivation, there are individual wards where the deprivation is equal to wards in Ipswich or Waveney (Lowestoft) including Fressingfield, Stowmarket South and Hoxne, on the Norfolk border near Diss. Hoxne is the site of one of the largest hoards of 4th and 5th century Roman gold and silver ever found in England.
description_4: Social Mobility: The area scrapes in at 64 to the top 65 hot-spots for social mobility in England.
description_5: Education: It has the highest percentage of young people achieving 5+ A* to C at GCSE (60.8%) in Suffolk, and also the highest percentage of young people going into Higher Education or other qualifications. Having said that, the District also has higher percentages of NEETs than elsewhere in Suffolk – only Ipswich and St Edmundsbury are higher.
description_6: Cultural Offer: Mid-Suffolk has a wide range of heritage assets including many restored post windmills in the Waveney valley, some beautiful churches and the Mid-Suffolk Light Railway. It also houses the nationally renowned Museum of East Anglian Life which recently received Arts Council National Portfolio Organisation status. Its proximity to Diss in the north means that many residents can take advantage of the programme at Diss Corn Hall, or to the west in Bury St Edmunds. Suffolk ArtLink based at Stradbroke specialises in programmes of work for and with young people and The Bank in Eye provides a small arts centre for local people, programming local art exhibitions, workshops and small scale music performance.

name: North Norfolk
description_1: North Norfolk is a largely unspoilt, sparsely populated rural landscape with a long and interesting coastline, making it one of the most sought after tourist destinations for Norfolk. There is a significant number of second homes and holiday cottages to rent which has forced local house prices up and out of the reach of many permanent residents.
description_2: Communities: North Norfolk has the lowest percentage of children and young people than any of the local authorities in Norfolk. The local authority has conversely an ageing population, which has risen by 20% in the past 10 years, causing a different set of issues for service providers in the District). Though there are lower rates of child poverty than county and national averages, these hide pockets of serious hidden needs and high levels of inequality in some wards. LSOAs with significant deprivation are found in Cromer, Fakenham, Stalham and North Walsham: in fact 29.5% of children under 16 live in income-deprived households in North Walsham East ward. These areas also have households with the least access to a car or van, making transport difficult, even though there is a regular train service from Sheringham to Norwich. However none of North Norfolk’s wards are actually in the highest 10% for indices of deprivation.
description_3: In terms of participation by children and young people, the lower numbers are to be expected. However schools in the area try hard fill this gap. Active library borrowers in North Norfolk among this age group are actually above average for the county.
description_4: Education: attainment is around average at all levels.
description_5: Social Mobility: North Norfolk does not have a good record on social mobility. It features among the worst performing 20% of authorities, at 45 out of 65, though other parts of Norfolk score worse than that.
description_6: Cultural Offer: North Norfolk has a thriving cultural scene. Its north facing coast and beautiful countryside means that it is home to around 300 practising visual artists, sculptors and craft makers, supported by a network of festivals, exhibition, commercial galleries and shops. Sheringham Little Theatre runs a year round programme of theatrical productions as well as community cinema, and has a well established youth outreach programme across the District. There are several interesting and specialist local museums in Cromer, Fakenham and Sheringham, along with the Museum of the Broads at Stalham, plus architectural and industrial heritage sites ranging from the grandiose Holkham Hall to the North Norfolk Steam Railway, running regularly during the season from Sheringham to Holt.

name: Norwich
description_1: Norwich is the county town of Norfolk, being the administrative centre for Norfolk County council and for Norwich City Council. It is the key urban area for the whole county, and a key economic driver – it is the largest labour market in the East of England and also the fifth most popular retail centre in England. It is also an important tourist and cultural centre with many historic buildings, both domestic and especially ecclesiastical, and a gateway to the Norfolk Broads.
description_2: Communities: Norwich has significant areas of deprivation on its peripheries, and this impacts on children and young people. Around 30,000 children and young people from 0-19 live in Norwich, making 22.1% of the population, of which 26% are living in poverty. While there is a higher percentage young people involved in positive activities, Norwich has a high number of safeguarding interventions and there is the highest percentage of NEETs in Norfolk (around 9% as opposed to the average of 5% for the county).
description_3: Social Mobility: In spite of this, the 2016 Social Mobility Index placed Norwich as the second worst area for Social Mobility for children and young people from deprived backgrounds.
description_4: Education: While educational attainment is below average, it is improving.
description_5: Cultural Offer: The City is a centre of national and international culture and arts with two world class universities (University of East Anglia and Norwich University of the Arts), a 1600 seater theatre in Norwich Theatre Royal, a beautiful medieval cathedral, important museums and the Millennium Library which has the highest footfall of any UK library, a vibrant independent music scene plus several important arts organisations including Norfolk and Norwich Festival, Writers Centre Norwich, Norwich Arts Centre and the Castle Museum. All these organisations and many others provide programmes for children and young people aiming to counter some of the disadvantage and inequalities evident in the city.

name: Peterborough
description_1: See layer or move to ward layers

name: South Cambridgeshire
description_1: South Cambridgeshire is Cambridgeshire’s most prosperous District outside Cambridge. With a population of around 150,000, it surrounds Cambridge, though the bulk of the geographic area is south of the City, bordering Hertfordshire, Essex and Suffolk. Its population is increasing rapidly, especially through the building of new towns; the existing Camborne and in development Northstowe.
description_2: Employment and Education: Its proximity to Cambridge and its access to fast trains to London mean that unemployment is well below the national average at 1.5% and educational attainment is generally good ranking in the 2nd highest sextile in the 2016 Education White Paper.
description_3: While large parts of South Cambridgeshire are agricultural, the professional, scientific and technical sector is by far the largest in the District, not surprising due to its proximity to Cambridge. Information and communication come second.
description_4: Communities: South Cambridgeshire is also the least deprived of Cambridgeshire’s Districts. It ranks 319th of 354 Districts across England, where 1 is the most deprived. However this ranking has declined between 2010 and 2015, making some LSOAs more deprived, mainly in the domains of Barriers to Housing and Income, but these are minor compared to the rest of Cambridgeshire. It does not appear in the Social Mobility Index’s top 20% of social mobility hotspots, yet the scores very poorly for ‘youth’ ranking 306 out of 324 districts in the country.
description_5: Cultural Offer: There are some major cultural assets in South Cambridgeshire, especially Wysing Arts (an ACE NPO for the visual arts) at Bourne; Imperial War Museum Duxford, Europe’s premier aviation museum; Wimpole Hall and Par; Chilford Hall Vineyard and Winery; Denny Abbey and the Farmland Museum north of Cambridge, and of course Grantchester on the edge of Cambridge, made famous by the poet Rupert Brooke.

name: South Norfolk
description_1: South Norfolk District lies to the south of Norwich. Its northerly area is urbanised as it is part of greater Norwich, but the majority of the District is rural, with agriculture as its major industry.
description_2: Communities: The District is the most prosperous overall in terms of outcomes for children and young people than any other Borough or District in Norfolk. It has much lower rates of child poverty and children living in income deprivation (CLIID) than both Norfolk and England, but there are pockets of high inequality in some wards. For instance child poverty is less than 1% in parts of Abbey and Roydon, compared to 53% in Old Costessey (part of greater Norwich), and Diss has LSOAs with significant child poverty, at 28.7% compared to say, Brooke, at only 2.3%.
description_3: There are high levels of participation in positive leisure activity in South Norfolk which is to be expected particularly for families living closer to Norwich who have their own transport. There are fewer households without personal transport than any other District or Borough in Norfolk. Public transport links are patchy, though there are direct train links with Norwich both via Diss and via Wymondham.
description_4: Education: achievement is above average, better than anywhere else in Norfolk. However it is the only District that shows significant imbalances between the achievement of disadvantaged children and others at both KS2 and KS4, and this gap is the largest in Norfolk.
description_5: Social Mobility: in South Norfolk is better than anywhere else in the county, though it is still not in the top 20% hotspots in England.
description_6: Cultural Offer: South Norfolk has fewer cultural assets than other parts of Norfolk. Families in the north or with their own transport can of course take advantage of the proximity of Norwich. The Corn Hall in Diss is an arts venue, and Creative Arts East, based in Wymondham, has a county and regional remit to programme touring theatre and cinema to rural community settings, and also runs a young producers’ programme. However it does not run a venue in its own right.  There are a number of heritage sites and museums, including two WW! Memorial museums, the Bressingham Steam Museum and Caistor Roman Town. Wymondham Abbey is an important medieval building part of which is still used for services and concerts.

name: St Edmundsbury
description_1: St Edmundsbury District Council is centred on the historic market town of Bury St Edmunds. With its largely 18th century town housing alongside the remains of the medieval abbey of St Edmund and the newly restored Cathedral church, it is an important tourist destination with particular literary connections – Dickens located part of The Pickwick Papers at the Angel Inn.
description_2: An emerging Local Cultural Education Partnership, the Heart of East Anglia, is developing to serve this area.
description_3: Communities: The town is quite prosperous, one of the only second-tier local authorities in Suffolk that has improved its ranking in terms of indices of deprivation. Bury St Edmunds benefits from ‘the Cambridge effect’ due to its proximity to the A14, a regular service to Cambridge and good schools. Bury St Edmunds is also the base for West Suffolk College – this further education institution draws its students from across west Suffolk and even from Brandon and Thetford in Norfolk. The countryside surrounding Bury Edmunds is considered to be very attractive and contains some important heritage buildings and churches.
description_4: However, as elsewhere in Suffolk, this prosperous exterior does hide significant pockets of deprivation, particularly in terms of access to affordable housing in Bury St Edmunds itself, and for the rural villages and towns, such as Haverhill, to employment and transport links and access to services such as GP surgeries and post offices.
description_5: Cultural Offer: Bury St Edmunds itself is home to the Theatre Royal, one of the few remaining 18th century theatres in the UK now owned by the National Trust, but still offering a full programme of plays and concerts, and a strong outreach programme. Other major cultural assets in the District are the Apex (a large modern venue in Bury St Edmund’s), a small but active arts centre in Haverhill, some small museums, and historic houses such as Ickworth and Hengrave Hall. Bury St Edmunds also hosts the well-established annual Bury St Edmund’s Festival – one which is mainly though not exclusively music-based.

name: Suffolk Coastal
description_1: Suffolk Coastal District combined administratively and democratically with Waveney in 2017 as East Suffolk. Suffolk Coastal is a largely rural District, which as its name suggests, is entirely bounded on the eastern side by the North Sea. It runs straight down the coast from just south of Lowestoft to the port of Felixstowe at the mouth of the Orwell estuary. On the west and north its boundaries connect with Waveney, Mid-Suffolk and Ipswich. The District has the main A12 running through it and has a rail connection running from Lowestoft to Ipswich via Woodbridge. Its coastal beaches and wildlife reserves are a magnet for tourists, and tourism services are its biggest employers. It also has a major strategic nuclear power station, Sizewell B, on the coast between Dunwich and Leiston, and the port of Felixstowe is one of the largest container ports in Europe.
description_2: Communities: Suffolk Coastal is, alongside Mid-Suffolk, one of the most prosperous Districts in Suffolk, though even here its relative deprivation has increased between 2010 and 2015 compared to its statistical neighbours. As elsewhere in Suffolk the overall prosperity of Suffolk Coastal masks considerable inequalities – for instance, the ward of Fexistowe West is among the most deprived in Suffolk, and the villages of Peasnall, Walberswick (just across the river from Southwold), and Hacheston (close to Snape) all have significant pockets of deprivation.
description_3: Social Mobility:  In terms of social mobility it is median, neither one of the Social Mobility Index’s top 20% of hotspots, nor in its bottom 20% of coldspots.
description_4: Education: Like Mid-Suffolk, levels of educational achievement is higher than average, with around 55% of pupils going on to higher education or other further education, though the number of NEETs is above average for the rest of Suffolk.
description_5: Cultural Offer: Suffolk Coastal has many important cultural assets. Among the most important is the internationally renowned Snape Maltings, home of the Benjamin Britten Foundation and alongside Aldeburgh the centre for the annual Aldeburgh Music Festival and Aldeburgh Literature Festival. Heritage sites include Dunwich – the vanished village under the sea which has its own museum – and Framlingham Castle, as well as many important wildlife conservation sites, many owned and managed by the National Trust and the RSPB. Other local museums include the Tide Mill Living Museum in Woodbridge, Martello Tower ‘P’ in Felixstowe, the Long Shop Museum in Leiston and The Red House, Aldeburgh, home of composer Benjamin Britten.

name: Waveney
description_1: Waveney District borders Norfolk along the Waveney valley and includes part of the southern Broads National Park. Although much is very rural, more than 50% of the population live in Lowestoft, on the coast at the mouth of the Waveney. Lowestoft, like Great Yarmouth to the north, was once a popular coastal resort but which has declined considerably in recent decades leaving pockets of extreme deprivation – Lowestoft has some of the 10% most deprived wards in England. However, the town has the potential to regenerate, especially through revitalising tourism and through servicing the growing off-shore energy industry. The Waveney Valley is a tourist destination in its own right, with Beccles, Halesworth and Bungay its main towns. Southwold is an unspoilt coastal town to the south of the District, on the borders with Suffolk Coastal District, and is a well-known tourist destination with literary and theatrical associations, as well as being the home of Adnams Brewery.
description_2: Lowestoft Rising is the established Local Cultural Education Partnership serving the town of Lowestoft.
description_3: Communities:  Lowestoft has a high number of deprived wards. Around 13% of the residents of Lowestoft aged between 16 and 64 are on some sort of benefit payment, and educational achievement in the town is poor. Through the multi-agency regeneration partnership Lowestoft Rising key community issues are being addressed. There are significant pockets of deprivation in Beccles and Bungay as well, with LSOAs in the 20% most deprived in England, and over 22% of children in Waveney live in income deprived households.
description_4: Education: In 2015, only 41.6% of pupils gained 5+ A*-C at GCSE (including English and Maths) and in some LSOAs the average was less than 25% with one at only 11%. Only 43.1% of pupils went on to higher education in the whole of Waveney, and the number of NEETs at 18 at 8% is the highest in Suffolk, with most of these in Lowestoft.
description_5: Cultural Offer: Waveney has many cultural assets. One of the biggest festivals, Latitude, has established itself in  Henham Park near Southwold – more than just a music festival with bands and acts from all over the world, it provides an eclectic mix of live literature, comedy, even ballroom dancing. The Cut at Halesworth is a multi-use arts festival that hosts both the annual Halesworth Arts Festival, and the new INK Festival for new writing for film and theatre with an East Anglian connection. There are two theatres in Lowestoft – the Marina and the Seagull – and as well as interesting heritage sites such as Somerleyton Hall and St Peters Brewery, based in a moated medieval house, there are many local museums – Lowestoft Museum and Lowestoft Maritime Museums, the East Anglian Transport Museum at Carlton Colville on the edge of Lowestoft, plus local museums in Beccles and Halesworth.
